SIMPLE: undern
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Undern
<hw>Un"dern</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS.
<ets>undern</ets>; akin to OS. <ets>undorn</ets>, OHG.
<ets>untarn</ets>, <ets>untorn</ets>, Icel. <ets>undorn</ets> mid
afternoon, mid forenoon, Goth. <ets>unda⟦uacute⟧rnimats</ets> the midday
meal. Cf. <er>Undermeal</er>, <er>Undertime</er>.]</ety> <def>The time
between; the time between sunrise and noon; specifically, the third hour
of the day, or nine o'clock in the morning, according to ancient
reckoning; hence, mealtime, because formerly the principal meal was
eaten at that hour; also, later, the afternoon; the time between dinner
and supper.</def> <mark>[Obs. or Prov. Eng.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Betwixt <qex>undern</qex> and noon was the field all won.</q>
<rj><qau>R. of Brunne.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In a bed of worts still he lay⟦br⟧
Till it was past <qex>undern</qex> of the day.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Underneath</ent>⟦br⟧
